    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-13T11:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-13T11:30:00-05:00" n="143"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d143">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/4671: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Valencia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-13T12:00:00-04:30"
                            >February 13, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>X–501. My [X–]499, February 12, 6 p.m.<note n="35" xml:id="d143fn35">Not
                        printed.</note> Today’s papers report the approval by all political parties
                    and syndical organizations of the following program: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The Government to possess all powers.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>General mobilization and compulsory military service.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Intensification of work on coast defenses.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Creation of war industries under Government control.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Unified command.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>Fulfillment of its functions by council of war.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>“Purification” of all important military commands placing in them
                            persons of absolute ability and loyalty to the present state.</item>
                        <label>8.</label>
                        <item>All arms to be in charge of Government.</item>
                        <label>9.</label>
                        <item>Establishment of efficient maritime and coast guard services.</item>
                        <label>10.</label>
                        <item>Restoration of effectiveness to police force.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>No mention is made of the dangerous proposal to curtail the display of the
                    social-political flags and emblems.</p>
                <p>The response to the U. G. T.<note n="36" xml:id="d143fn36">Union General de
                        Trabajadores.</note> invitation to participate in tomorrow’s “manifestation”
                    appears to have been unanimously favorable with the exception of the F. A.
                        I.<note n="37" xml:id="d143fn37">Federación Anarquista Ibérica.</note> which
                    has refused. The official organ of this <pb facs="0253" n="241" xml:id="pg_241"
                    /> organization continues its defiant tone and in an editorial today states that
                    there is no institution in Spain superior to the C. N. T.,<note n="38"
                        xml:id="d143fn38">Confederación Nacional de Trabajo.</note> U. G. T., and F.
                    A. I., and rejects the idea of amalgamating their armed forces with those of the
                    Government—which it says must be changed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
